{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01MkaoyyeDnjgamYkpcLPjrm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Aha! So the buggy commit changed:\n1. Removed `#include <inttypes.h>`\n2. Changed `uint8_t yr_lowercase[256]` to `char yr_lowercase[256]`\n3. Changed `uint8_t yr_altercase[256]` to `char yr_altercase[256]`\n\nThe problem is that `char` is SIGNED on most platforms (whereas `uint8_t` is UNSIGNED). This means if any byte value is > 127 (like 0xE0), it will be interpreted as a negative number when stored in a signed char.\n\nThis is likely causing issues with the regex matching logic when dealing with non-ASCII characters (bytes > 127).\n\nLet me check where these tables are used and how they might affect the regex matching. Let me also run the test with GDB to see what's happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":772,"cache_read_input_tokens":44116,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":772},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3b5bc1dc-71cc-41aa-984b-77d6fdcad658","uuid":"36c2c8e3-e596-41ff-8a0e-eeaccba8c845"}
