{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01YPP6VkvFGc2sFmZP67hWjo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Perfect! So in commit f8fe4f05 (before the buggy commit), the arrays were declared as `uint8_t`. The buggy commit changed them to `char`, which is the problem.\n\nNow let me verify my understanding by checking how the regex engine handles character classes with case-insensitive matching. The key issue is:\n\n1. Input byte: 0xE0 (224)\n2. yr_altercase[224] in buggy version returns a signed char which is -32\n3. When -32 is used in the CHAR_IN_CLASS macro as `chr`, it calculates -32/8 = -4\n4. This causes out-of-bounds access to the bitmap array\n\nThe test case is:\n```\n\"rule test { strings: $a =/abc([^\\\"\\\\\\\\])*\\\"/ nocase condition: $a }\"\n```\n\nWith the `nocase` flag, the character class matching uses yr_altercase to check for alternate case, which triggers the bug.\n\nThe fix is to change `char` back to `uint8_t` for both yr_lowercase and yr_altercase declarations in both the header and implementation files.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":690,"cache_read_input_tokens":53270,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":690},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3b5bc1dc-71cc-41aa-984b-77d6fdcad658","uuid":"524f1f80-4759-48a0-badf-56ef02335136"}
